# Pull requests

## Shell: use Bash for `gh` (and similar CLIs)

**zsh** in this environment may not load `GH_TOKEN` or other GitHub env vars. Always invoke the GitHub CLI (and any other tool that relies on Bash login/profile exports) via **Bash**:

```bash
bash -lc 'gh pr create --base main --head feature/your-branch --title "..." --body "..."'
bash -lc 'gh pr list'
bash -lc 'gh auth status'
```

Agents and scripts should wrap `gh …` in **`bash -lc '…'`** (single-quoted inner command) instead of calling `gh` directly from the default **zsh** session. Use the same pattern for any CLI that only picks up tokens or API keys from Bash login/profile files.

Before `gh pr create` or finalizing a PR, follow **`.cursor/rules/git-workflow.mdc`**: **`git fetch origin`** and **`git pull origin main`** on the PR branch so `main` is integrated and conflicts are resolved locally.

When creating or drafting a pull request for this repository (including via `gh pr create`):

1. Read and follow **`.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`** — the PR title and body must include every section from that template: **Summary**, **Type of change** (checkboxes), **Changes**, **How to test**, and **Checklist** (checkboxes).
2. Fill each section with concrete, accurate detail (what changed, why, how to verify, risk notes). Do not submit a one-line PR description.
3. Prefer `gh pr create --body-file` with a complete body, or paste the filled template into `--body`, so GitHub receives the full structure.

The template is the single source of truth for PR format in this project.
